(2202, 6, '2015-05-28 21:39:15', '2015-05-28 21:39:15', '<a href="http://localhost:8888/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/media1.jpg"><img class="  aligncenter wp-image-2203" title="influencer marketing campaigns" src="http://localhost:8888/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/media1.jpg" alt="influencer marketing campaigns" width="672" height="448" /></a>\r\n\r\nIt\'s easy for brands to assume that content creators participate in influencer marketing campaigns because it\'s all about the money. While financial compensation is part of the equation, there are many other motivations such as prestige, linkages with brands, audience growth, and audience-relevant content generation. Yet, the better you understand the wide range of prospective and sometimes complex motivations that content creators have for taking part in influence campaigns, the more effectively you’ll be able to craft campaigns that intrigue the influencers you want to reach. Here’s a closer look at the most common reasons content creators become part of influencer marketing campaigns.<!--more-->\r\n<h2>Financial Compensation</h2>\r\nLet’s launch the discussion with the most straightforward motivation. Content creators are providing a service by developing content about your brand or product and sharing it with their audience. As a result, they’re being paid for both the effort and the results that work will generate. Incentives come in many different forms: flat payments, performance driven metrics based on engagement, or scaled payments based on audience reach.\r\n\r\nIn some cases, there may be bonuses for ongoing relationships or campaigns that exceed high-level metrics. Other forms of compensation that have monetary value but aren’t cash payments include free products, sponsored trips or free travel and admission to events. Financial compensation from influencer campaigns often helps content creators generate the cash flow to create content about what they care about the most.\r\n<h2>Relationships with Brands</h2>\r\nToday, content creators are an independent breed of free agents. Whether it’s a full-time job or just a lucrative hobby, today’s creators have to develop their own brands, cultivate an audience and find unique ways to monetize that following. Staff jobs at companies or publications are rarer than ever before; frankly, these entrepreneurial types often do better financially on their own, with the added benefits of creative freedom.\r\n\r\nConnections with brands provide content creators with several benefits. One is monetary, as already discussed. Another is legitimacy. A content creator that can say he or she worked on a campaign for a large brand may find the doors opening to other deals, from paid campaigns to sponsorships to other unrelated projects. Being affiliated with powerful brands helps position the content creator as a professional and an expert, and that’s a clear advantage in long-term career planning in today’s competitive marketplace.\r\n<h2>Expanded Exposure</h2>\r\nWhile it may seem counterintuitive, influencers connect with brand campaigns because it helps expand their own reach. As a result of branded campaign participation, companies hope that influencer content will attract their brands new followers, encourage purchases, and more. But influencers can also benefit in growing their own audiences during the process.\r\n\r\nOften, brands promote influencer content to their existing audiences and social channels, who may convert into followers and fans for the content creator. In addition, investments in expanded distribution or advertising can give tremendous exposure to the content – way beyond what the creator themselves could afford to invest. A virtuous cycle of exposure helps build awareness of all brands showcased during an influence campaign.\r\n<h2>Supporting What They Believe In</h2>\r\nMost content creators launched their careers on the basis of something powerful: passion for a particular topic or belief in a specific cause. Whether they’re committed to sharing the music of young urban artists or have an insatiable interest in the newest fashion trends, content creation gives these people a platform. Their followers become a community, and they get positive reinforcement for being part of the larger conversation.\r\n\r\nOne of the benefits of taking part in influencer campaigns allows these passionate fans in a specific space to get an inside view of a topic they care about. They have the opportunity to align with brands they’ve long admired. Creating content for a branded campaign allows a creator to put their original stamp or perspective on the space. These kinds of intrinsic motivations and rewards are often just as important as money.\r\n<h2>Creative Inspiration</h2>\r\nDeveloping content every day is a creatively demanding process. Coming up with new ideas around the same subject can wear down even the most dedicated and prolific creator. Successful content creators are constantly seeking new sources of content ideas. Participating in a brand-related influencer marketing campaign can reinvigorate a content creator’s development efforts.\r\n\r\nBy being exposed to the latest products or messages in their space, content creators are challenged to develop cutting-edge material that audiences will love. Campaign guidelines encourage innovation within certain boundaries. Sometimes campaigns are as simple as being able to offer competitions or free items to an influencer’s following. In other cases, it opens the door to creative expression and developing something that’s funny, moving, or educational. In whatever way, participating in an influencer campaign encourages creative inspiration and innovation for creators under pressure to constantly be pushing the envelope in their social video creation.\r\n\r\nAre you interested in learning more about reaching the right influencers to support your brand or message? <a href="http://localhost:8888/brands/">Contact FullBottle today</a> to learn more about our solutions and services.', 'Why Do Content Creators Really Get Involved in Influencer Marketing Campaigns?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'why-do-content-creators-really-get-involved-in-influencer-marketing-campaigns', '', '', '2015-05-28 21:39:15', '2015-05-28 21:39:15', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/?p=2202', 0, 'post', '', 0),
